# Cheat Sheet — Selection (if / else)

Quick review of Lesson 05.

---

## 1. What is selection?

Selection lets your program **choose** between different paths.

It uses a **predicate** (true/false expression) to decide which block runs.

---

## 2. Basic `if`

```d
int n = 10;

if (n > 5)
{
    writeln ("Greater than 5");
}
```

If the predicate is **true**, the block runs.  
If **false**, it is skipped.

---

## 3. `if` / `else`

```d
int n = 3;

if (n > 5)
{
    writeln ("Greater");
}
else
{
    writeln ("Not greater");
}
```

Only one block runs.

---

## 4. `else if`

```d
int n = 7;

if (n > 10)
{
    writeln ("Big");
}
else if (n > 5)
{
    writeln ("Medium");
}
else
{
    writeln ("Small");
}
```

The first true predicate wins.

---

## 5. Predicates you know so far

- `==` equal  
- `!=` not equal  
- `<` less than  
- `>` greater than  
- `<=` less than or equal  
- `>=` greater than or equal  

Predicates produce **true** or **false**.

---

## 6. Dual Truth

Every predicate has two possible outcomes:

- **true** → block runs  
- **false** → block does not run  

This is the foundation of selection.

See **notes/05-selection.md** for deeper review of Dual Truth.

---

## 7. Common beginner mistakes

### Using `=` instead of `==`
```d
if (n = 5) { }   // wrong: assignment
```

Correct:
```d
if (n == 5) { }
```

### Forgetting braces
```d
if (n > 5)
    writeln ("OK");
    writeln ("Done");   // always runs
```

### Writing unreachable code
```d
if (true)
{
    writeln ("Always");
}
else
{
    writeln ("Never");   // unreachable
}
```

